explanation:
Reasons each symbol is required to determine if any operations in OS_CloseFileByName are dead code:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER
  - This macro governs early-return or error handling when Filename is NULL. Its exact behavior (return value, longjmp, assert/abort, or no-op) changes whether the rest of the function can execute and thus whether subsequent statements could be dead.

- OS_FS_ERR_PATH_INVALID
  - The initial value assigned to return_code. To judge whether assigning this value is necessary (or removable) you must know its semantic role and whether it is ever used by callers — i.e., whether keeping or removing that assignment affects observable behavior.

- OS_SUCCESS
  - Used in the branch that updates return_code based on close_code. Knowing its numeric value and semantics is required to determine whether the conditional and assignment of return_code can change program behavior (thus not dead).

- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE
  - The object-type selector passed to OS_ObjectIdIterateActive controls which table/entries are iterated. Whether the loop runs at all (and so whether its body is dead) depends on what this constant selects.

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext
  - Drives the loop iteration (loop condition). Its iteration semantics (when it returns true/false, whether it advances token, whether it can always return false) determine whether the loop body executes and whether code inside the loop could be dead.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET
  - Macro used to map the iterator token to an entry in the object table. Its expansion (indexing, bounds checks, possible side effects) determines whether the stream pointer can be NULL/invalid and whether the access to stream->socket_domain/stream_name is meaningful or redundant.

- OS_stream_table
  - The actual table referenced by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET. The layout/content (size, entries for the selected LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE) affects whether the iterator yields valid stream entries and therefore whether the comparisons and close operations in the loop are ever executed.

- OS_stream_internal_record_t
  - The type of stream entries. You need its definition (members and their types) to determine whether fields used in the function (socket_domain, stream_name) exist, have side effects on access, or could be constant/unused.

- OS_object_iter_t
  - The iterator structure (fields such as token) is required to understand iterator state, whether OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry is actually processing the same entry referenced by token, and whether accesses/assignments depend on iterator semantics.

- OS_SocketDomain_INVALID
  - The specific enum/constant compared to stream->socket_domain. To decide if the socket_domain check ever holds (or is redundant) you must know possible domain values and whether streams of the iterated type can have non-invalid domains.

- strcmp
  - The string comparison determines matching by name. Its semantics (e.g., handling of NULL pointers, locale) and whether stream->stream_name can equal Filename govern whether the conditional can be true and therefore whether the close call and related logic are reachable/meaningful.

- OS_FileIteratorClose
  - The callback passed to OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry which performs the actual close. To decide if the call to OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry (and the update of return_code based on close_code) affects observable behavior, you must know what this close callback does (side effects) and whether it is necessary.

In combination these symbols determine: whether the loop ever executes; whether the conditional inside it can be true; whether the close operation has observable side-effects; and whether initializations and assignments (e.g., setting return_code) are required. That information is needed to decide if any executed operation in OS_CloseFileByName could be removed without changing program behaviour (i.e., is dead code).
